  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "回 Background: Diffusion Schrodinger Bridge (SB) ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      4,
      537,
      438,
      565
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Given two probability distributions $\\mathsf { p } _ { 0 } , \\mathsf { p } _ { 1 } ,$ how to transform $\\mathsf { p } _ { 0 }$ to $\\mathsf { p } _ { 1 }$ via adiffusion process and preserve the input-output similarity? ",
    "bbox": [
      68,
      570,
      391,
      604
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "1.Formulation of the Schrodinger Bridge Problem: ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      18,
      617,
      220,
      632
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "For two continuous distributions $\\pmb { p } _ { 0 }$ and $p _ { 1 }$ on $\\mathbb { R } ^ { D }$ ，isthe Schrodinger bridge problem: ",
    "bbox": [
      18,
      632,
      224,
      661
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\inf  _ {T \\in \\mathcal {F} (p _ {0}, p _ {1})} K L (T | | W ^ {\\epsilon}),\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      81,
      669,
      161,
      693
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "where $\\mathcal { F } ( p _ { 0 } , p _ { 1 } )$ are stochastic processes with marginals $\\pmb { p } _ { 0 }$ $_ { p _ { 1 } }$ at $t = 0$ and $t = 1$ ,respectively，while $W ^ { \\epsilon }$ is the Wiener processwithvariance∈,i.e.，given by the SDE: ",
    "bbox": [
      18,
      700,
      224,
      743
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\nW ^ {\\epsilon}: \\quad d X _ {t} = \\sqrt {\\epsilon} d W _ {t}.\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      81,
      752,
      161,
      766
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "This problem has a unique solution,which is a diffusion process $\\tau ^ { * }$ described bythe SDE: ",
    "bbox": [
      18,
      775,
      222,
      803
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\nT ^ {*}: \\quad d X _ {t} = g ^ {*} (X _ {t}, t) d t + \\sqrt {\\epsilon} d W _ {t}.\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      57,
      812,
      184,
      828
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/Light Schrödinger Bridge_poster/visuals/images/fig_7.jpg",
    "image_caption": [],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      27,
      839,
      202,
      938
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "The minimizer T* ",
    "bbox": [
      79,
      951,
      150,
      963
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "is called the Schrodinger Bridge. ",
    "bbox": [
      51,
      964,
      179,
      978
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "2. Structure of the Schrodinger Bridge. ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      247,
      614,
      406,
      629
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "The Schrodinger bridge problem can be fully characterized bythe initial distribution $\\pmb { p } _ { 0 }$ andthe Schrodingerpotential $\\phi ^ { * } ( x ) : \\mathbb { R } ^ { D }  \\mathbb { R } _ { + }$ .The optimal drift can be expressed by the Schrodinger potential as ",
    "bbox": [
      247,
      630,
      453,
      687
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\ng ^ {*} (x, t) = \\epsilon \\nabla_ {x} \\log \\int_ {\\mathbb {R} ^ {D}} \\mathcal {N} \\left(x ^ {\\prime} | x, (1 - t) \\epsilon I _ {D}\\right) \\phi^ {*} \\left(x ^ {\\prime}\\right) d x ^ {\\prime}\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      258,
      693,
      440,
      727
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "$\\begin{array} { r } { v ^ { * } ( x _ { 1 } ) \\stackrel { \\mathrm { d e f } } { = } \\exp ( - \\frac { \\| x _ { 1 } \\| ^ { 2 } } { 2 \\epsilon } ) \\phi ^ { * } ( x _ { 1 } ) } \\end{array}$ ",
    "bbox": [
      247,
      734,
      452,
      767
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "3.Integration of the Schrodinger Bridge SDE. ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      247,
      784,
      433,
      799
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "The Schrodinger bridge SDE: ",
    "bbox": [
      248,
      800,
      350,
      814
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\nT ^ {*}: \\quad d X _ {t} = g ^ {*} (X _ {t}, t) d t + \\sqrt {\\epsilon} d W _ {t}.\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      287,
      822,
      413,
      838
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "admitsa closed-form solution $\\pi ^ { * } ( x _ { 1 } | x _ { 0 } )$ expressed through theadjusted Schrodinger potential $v ^ { * }$ ",
    "bbox": [
      247,
      846,
      452,
      875
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\pi^ {*} (x _ {1} | x _ {0}) \\stackrel {\\text {d e f}} {=} \\frac {\\exp (\\langle x _ {0} , x _ {1} \\rangle / \\epsilon) v ^ {*} (x _ {1})}{c ^ {*} (x _ {0})},\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      286,
      882,
      414,
      916
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "where $\\begin{array} { r } { c ^ { * } ( x _ { 0 } ) \\ { \\stackrel { \\mathrm { d e f } } { = } } \\ \\int _ { \\mathbb { R } ^ { D } } \\exp \\left( \\langle x _ { 0 } , x _ { 1 } \\rangle / \\epsilon \\right) v ^ { * } ( x _ { 1 } ) d x _ { 1 } } \\end{array}$ is the normalizing constant. ",
    "bbox": [
      247,
      923,
      453,
      956
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "[II] Proposed Algorithm: Light Schrodinger Bridge (LightSB) ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      472,
      133,
      932,
      159
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Our solver is based on: ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      480,
      165,
      557,
      178
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "1.Optimal parameterization of the Schrodinger bridge using mixtures of Gaussians: ",
    "bbox": [
      480,
      180,
      754,
      194
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\nv _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {1}\\right) = \\sum_ {k = 1} ^ {K} \\alpha_ {k} \\mathcal {N} \\left(x _ {1} \\mid r _ {k}, \\epsilon S _ {k}\\right), \\quad c _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {0}\\right) = \\sum_ {k = 1} ^ {K} \\alpha_ {k} \\exp \\left(\\frac {x _ {0} ^ {T} S _ {k} x _ {0} + 2 r _ {k} ^ {T} x _ {0}}{2 \\epsilon}\\right).\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      496,
      204,
      738,
      241
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "2.New loss function for training the Schrodinger bridge: ",
    "bbox": [
      480,
      249,
      669,
      264
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\operatorname {K L} \\left(T ^ {*} \\mid \\mid T _ {\\theta}\\right) = \\underbrace {\\int_ {\\mathbb {R} ^ {D}} \\log c _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {0}\\right) p _ {0} \\left(x _ {0}\\right) d x _ {0} - \\int_ {\\mathbb {R} ^ {D}} \\log v _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {1}\\right) p _ {1} \\left(x _ {1}\\right) d x _ {1}} _ {\\mathcal {L} (\\theta)} + \\text {C o n s t}\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      496,
      271,
      739,
      320
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Advantages: ",
    "bbox": [
      486,
      335,
      564,
      353
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Fast training ",
    "bbox": [
      643,
      323,
      696,
      337
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "(<1 minute on 4 CPU cores, not hours of training on GPU,like others). ",
    "bbox": [
      585,
      337,
      755,
      362
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Algorithm 1: Light Schrodinger Bridge (LightSB) ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      760,
      174,
      958,
      190
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "repeat ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      760,
      198,
      789,
      212
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\text {S a m p l e} \\left\\{x _ {0} ^ {1}, \\dots , x _ {0} ^ {N} \\right\\} \\sim p _ {0}, \\left\\{x _ {1} ^ {1}, \\dots , x _ {1} ^ {M} \\right\\} \\sim p _ {1}; \\\\ \\widehat {\\mathcal {L}} _ {\\theta} \\leftarrow \\frac {1}{N} \\sum_ {n = 1} ^ {N} \\log c _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {0} ^ {n}\\right) - \\frac {1}{M} \\sum_ {m = 1} ^ {M} \\log v _ {\\theta} \\left(x _ {1} ^ {m}\\right); \\\\ \\text {U p d a t e} \\theta \\text {b y u s i n g} \\frac {\\partial \\widehat {\\mathcal {L}} _ {\\theta}}{\\partial \\theta}; \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      766,
      214,
      987,
      290
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "until converged; ",
    "bbox": [
      759,
      293,
      826,
      307
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Theoretical validity (the guarantees of the method's learningability from thepointof view of statistical learningand approximation theories). ",
    "bbox": [
      766,
      323,
      978,
      363
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
